PNG file format and retrieving image dimensions from it

  • Report this post
  • Quote
  •  

    31 Aug 2017, 07:24

    Before we begin:

    Reference from http://www.libpng.org
    PNG (Portable Network Graphics) Specification, Version 1.2
    • PNG Structure
    • Chunk layout
    • IHDR Image header
    • IEND Image trailer

    BIgEndian format:
    When we read a single RGB color from a 24bit bitmap for example DE CA FE, it appears in the same order in file, but File.ReadUINT() will return 16698078 (hex = 0xFECADE)
    The number appears to be in reverse because AutoHotkey ( => because of the OS it is written for: Windows => because of hardware Windows is written for: IBM-PC ) follows Little endian format for numbers.
    To know more, read: Understanding Big and Little Endian Byte Order

    In PNG files, all the numbers occur in Big Endian format.
    If an offset contains a hex like DE CA FE, we have to convert it to a number as is... like in this snippet: MsgBox % 0xDECAFE + 0

    The PNG file layout in layman terms:
    A png begins with a signature, a ANSI string "‰PNG" . "`r`n" . A_Space . "`n"
    followed by many sub-files in following structure:
    4 bytes: File size
    4 bytes: File type (a UNIQUE name)
    X bytes: File data as raw bytes (the bytes should match File size)
    4 bytes: CRC32 hash for File type + File data
    (next file follows)
    4 bytes: File size
    4 bytes: File type (a UNIQUE name)
    X bytes: File data as actual raw bytes (the bytes should match File size)
    4 bytes: CRC32 hash for File type + File data
    ( .. and so on)

    To parse and find a sub-file
    Read the first 8 bytes and check if it is a valid PNG signature
    Read next 8 bytes and check if file type is what you seek
    If not
    Seek the next offset by adding 4 to file size ( we have to add 4 to skip the CRC32 hash bytes occurring at the end of every file data )
    Read next 8 bytes and check if file type is what you seek
    if not
    rinse and repeat.

    Hope you get the concept... Now replace all "FILE" with "CHUNK" in above paragraphs, as that is how it is documented in PNG specs.



    Retrieving images dimensions from a PNG file

    A PNG file begins with a constant* 8 byte signature (in HEX): 89504E470D0A1A0A
    *This has never changed and will never change with future versions

    The dimensions of PNG image is stored in IHDR chunk, which always/or most coomonly occurs immediately after the signature.
    This the recommended specification and is followed by all spec-abiding image applications.
    The leading 24 bytes of a PNG file in enough for retrieving image dimension.

    Lets start by inspecting the 33 bytes of homepage logo


    The hex broken down

    Code: [Select all] [Download] (Untitled.txt)GeSHi © Codebox Plus

    89 50 4E 47 0D 0A 1A 0A                    ; PNG signature
    00 00 00 0D                                ; Chunk length     =  13 (Big Endian)
    49 48 44 52                                ; Chunk type code  =  IHDR
    00 00 00 F1 00 00 00 4E 08 03 00 00 00     ; Chunk data  
    C6 89 00 9B                                ; CRC32 (Big endian)


    We see above, that the first chunk data is IHDR (13 bytes), and has its own structure, broken down as follows:

    Code: [Select all] [Download] (Untitled.txt)GeSHi © Codebox Plus

    Width (Big Endian):  4 bytes = 00 00 00 F1   
    Height (Big Endian): 4 bytes = 00 00 00 4E 
    Bit depth            1 byte  = 08
    Color type           1 byte  = 03
    Compression method   1 byte  = 00
    Filter method        1 byte  = 00
    Interlace method     1 byte  = 00


    the dimensions of AHK logo is 241x78
    0x000000F1+0 = 241
    0x0000004E+0 = 78

    The above done with a script:

    Code: [Select all] [Expand] [Download] GeSHi © Codebox Plus

    #SingleInstance, Force
    SetWorkingDir %A_ScriptDir% 

    SrcPNG := "ahk-logo.png"
    If ! FileExist(SrcPNG)                           ; Downloads Source PNG when not available
         URLDownloadToFile, https://autohotkey.com/assets/images/ahk-logo-no-text241x78-180.png, %SrcPNG%
         
    FileRead, Bin, *c *m24 %SrcPNG% ; Read the leading 24 bytes 
    W := BinToHex( &Bin+16, 4, "0x"  ) + 0
    H := BinToHex( &Bin+20, 4, "0x"  ) + 0
    MsgbOx % W "x" H 

    BinToHex( P, Bytes := 4, Prefix := ""  ) { 
    Local Str := ""
    Loop % (Bytes)
       Str .= Format( "{:02X}", *(P+A_Index-1) ) 
    Return ( Prefix . Str )
    }


    All is well until we encounter a PNG that doesn't follow rules.
    According to PNG specs, a CHUNK with non-standard Chunk type should be ignored by parsing application.
    I couldn't find one, so I had to create one and tested if LoadPicture(,"GDI+") would load the file if IHDR was not the first chunk.
    It loads.. and every windows application recognizes it as normal PNG. IsPicture() is also compliant and locates IHDR by parsing, but only when if necessary.

    I tested by inserting a custom CHUNK between PNG Signature and IHDR chunk as follows:

    Code: [Select all] [Download] (Untitled.txt)GeSHi © Codebox Plus

    4 bytes: Chunk size = 10
    4 bytes: Chunk type = "AHK="
    10 bytes: Chunk data = "AutoHotkey"
    4 bytes: CRC32 = 0


    The script:

    Code: [Select all] [Expand] [Download] GeSHi © Codebox Plus

    #NoEnv
    #Warn
    #SingleInstance, Force
    SetWorkingDir %A_ScriptDir% 

    TrgPNG := "ahk-logo-modified.png" 
    SrcPNG := "ahk-logo.png"

    If ! FileExist(SrcPNG)                           ; Downloads Source PNG when not available
         URLDownloadToFile, https://autohotkey.com/assets/images/ahk-logo-no-text241x78-180.png, %SrcPNG%


    FileTrg := FileOpen(TrgPNG,"rw") 
    FileTrg.WriteINT64(0x0A1A0A0D474E5089)           ; Write PNG signature
    FileTrg.WriteUINT(0x0A000000)                    ; Size of Chunk data = 10 (Bigendian UINT)

    Saved := FileTrg.Encoding 
    FileTrg.Encoding := "cp0"
    FileTrg.Write("AHK=")                            ; Chunk type
    FileTrg.Write("AutoHotkey")                      ; Chunk data 
    FileTrg.Encoding := Saved

    FileTrg.WriteUINT(0)                             ; NOT Generating/filling CRC32 checksum

    FileSrc := FileOpen(SrcPNG,"r")                  ; Open source PNG
    FileSrc.Seek(8,0)                                ; Seek 8th byte from beginning
    sLen := FileSrc.Length()-8                       ; Filesize excluding header of 8 bytes 
    FileSrc.RawRead(Bin,sLen)                        ; Read file (excluding header) in to variable Bin
    FileSrc.Close()                                  

    FileTrg.RawWrite(Bin,sLen)                       ; Write oringinal PNG data to target PNG
    FileTrg.Close()

    Gui, Margin, 100, 100
    Gui, Add, Picture,, % "HBITMAP:" LoadPicture(TrgPNG)
    Gui, Show,,PNG with custom data
    Return


    The initial 55 bytes of ahk-logo-modified.png (created with above script), as hex:

    Code: [Select all] [Download] (Untitled.txt)GeSHi © Codebox Plus

    89 50 4E 47 0D 0A 1A 0A                ; PNG signature
    ; First chunk follows
    00 00 00 0A                            ; Chunk length = 10
    41 48 4B 3D                            ; chunk type   = AHK=
    41 75 74 6F 48 6F 74 6B 65 79          ; Chunk data   = AutoHotkey
    00 00 00 00                            ; CRC32
    ; Next chunk follows
    00 00 00 0D                            ; Chunk length = 13
    49 48 44 52                            ; Chunk type   = IHDR
    00 00 00 F1 00 00 00 4E 08 03 00 00 00 ; Chunk data
    C6 89 00 9B                            ; CRC 32


    I hope the above hex gives a good picture on PNG format.
    To know more about various PNG chunks, Read: Chunk Specifications

    PS: Next will be JPG format.

    Edit: Google Chrome doesn't display the image in the attachment, Internet Explorer does.
